---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout 
  title="What is AI Safety?"
  description="Understand AI safety: what it is, why it matters, and how DAISI helps students and academics work on alignment, governance, and safety."
>
  <script
    type="application/ld+json"
    slot="head"
    set:html={JSON.stringify({
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is AI safety?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "AI safety is the field working to ensure that increasingly capable AI systems remain beneficial and under meaningful human oversight — covering technical research, governance, and policy."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why is AI safety important?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "AI capabilities are advancing faster than our ability to understand or control these systems. Even experts who are sceptical of near-term timelines think human-level AI could arrive within a decade or two — which means the time to build safety foundations is now, not later."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How can I get involved in AI safety at Durham?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Start by attending our intro AIS101 sessions, join an in-depth reading group, and talk to us about research or policy projects. We support dissertation topics and applications to fellowships and external funding. See the Programmes and Get Involved pages for upcoming activities."
          }
        }
      ]
    })}
  />

  <!-- Hero / Title -->
  <section class="section section-neutral">
    <div class="site-container text-center">
      <h1 class="section-heading text-4xl md:text-5xl mb-4">What is AI Safety — and why does it matter?</h1>
      <div class="w-24 h-1 bg-gradient-to-r from-bright-purple to-light-purple mx-auto rounded-full mb-8"></div>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl max-w-2xl mx-auto leading-relaxed text-slate-600">
        A plain-language introduction — no prior knowledge needed, no hype.
      </p>

      <!-- Jump Navigation -->
      <nav class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-4 text-sm mt-8" aria-label="Page sections">
        <a href="#not-sci-fi" class="text-bright-purple hover:text-light-purple transition-colors font-medium">
          <i class="fas fa-shield-alt mr-1" aria-hidden="true"></i> Not science fiction
        </a>
        <span class="text-slate-400" aria-hidden="true">•</span>
        <a href="#the-problem" class="text-bright-purple hover:text-light-purple transition-colors font-medium">
          <i class="fas fa-exclamation-circle mr-1" aria-hidden="true"></i> The core problem
        </a>
        <span class="text-slate-400" aria-hidden="true">•</span>
        <a href="#what-is-being-done" class="text-bright-purple hover:text-light-purple transition-colors font-medium">
          <i class="fas fa-tools mr-1" aria-hidden="true"></i> What's being done
        </a>
        <span class="text-slate-400" aria-hidden="true">•</span>
        <a href="#getting-started" class="text-bright-purple hover:text-light-purple transition-colors font-medium">
          <i class="fas fa-rocket mr-1" aria-hidden="true"></i> Getting started
        </a>
      </nav>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 1: Not science fiction -->
  <section id="not-sci-fi" class="section section-neutral">
    <div class="site-container">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">

        <div class="text-center mb-12">
          <h2 class="section-heading text-3xl md:text-4xl mb-6">This isn't science fiction</h2>
          <div class="section-divider"></div>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card p-8 mb-8">
          <p class="text-lg md:text-xl leading-relaxed mb-0">
            A reasonable first reaction to "AI safety" is scepticism. Talk of superintelligence and existential risk can sound like science fiction — the kind of thing tech evangelists use to make their products sound important.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6 text-slate-700">
          That scepticism is worth taking seriously. But the people raising these concerns aren't fringe bloggers. Geoffrey Hinton and Yoshua Bengio — both Turing Award winners and two of the most cited AI researchers in the world — have shifted focus toward warning about the risks of the systems they helped create. Hinton left Google in 2023 specifically so he could speak freely about those risks. When he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2024, he used the platform to raise the alarm about AI. These are not people prone to hype.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6 text-slate-700">
          Governments have reached similar conclusions. The UK and EU have both established dedicated AI safety bodies. In 2023, over 350 AI researchers and executives — including the CEOs of OpenAI, Anthropic, and Google DeepMind — signed a statement declaring that "mitigating the risk of extinction from AI should be a global priority alongside other societal-scale risks such as pandemics and nuclear war."
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-8 text-slate-700">
          And crucially, even experts who push back hard on the most dramatic near-term claims still think advanced AI could arrive within a decade or two. Helen Toner — a former OpenAI board member and director at Georgetown's Center for Security and Emerging Technology — put it plainly:
        </p>

        <!-- Toner blockquote -->
        <blockquote class="info-card p-8 mb-8 border-l-4 border-bright-purple">
          <p class="text-lg md:text-xl leading-relaxed italic mb-4">
            "Dismissing discussion of AGI, human-level AI, transformative AI, superintelligence, etc. as 'science fiction' should be seen as a sign of total unseriousness. Time travel is science fiction. Martians are science fiction. 'Even many sceptical experts think we may well build it in the next decade or two' is not science fiction."
          </p>
          <footer class="text-sm text-slate-500 not-italic">
            — Helen Toner, <a href="https://helentoner.substack.com/p/long-timelines-to-advanced-ai-have?utm_source=bluedot-impact" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-bright-purple hover:underline inline-flex items-center gap-1">"Long timelines to advanced AI have gotten crazy short" <i class="fas fa-external-link-alt text-xs" aria-hidden="true"></i></a>, Rising Tide, April 2025
          </footer>
        </blockquote>

        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-slate-700">
          In other words: you don't have to believe the most dramatic forecasts to conclude that something important is happening, and that we are underprepared for it.
        </p>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 2: The core problem -->
  <section id="the-problem" class="section section-light">
    <div class="site-container">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">

        <div class="text-center mb-12">
          <h2 class="section-heading text-3xl md:text-4xl mb-6">So what's the actual problem?</h2>
          <div class="section-divider"></div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-8 text-slate-700">
          AI safety isn't one problem — it's a cluster of related engineering and governance challenges that get harder as these systems become more capable. Here are the three that researchers focus on most.
        </p>

        <!-- Three problems -->
        <div class="space-y-6 mb-12">

          <div class="info-card p-8">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-6">
              <div class="w-14 h-14 bg-gradient-to-br from-bright-purple to-light-purple rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
                <i class="fas fa-search text-2xl text-white" aria-hidden="true"></i>
              </div>
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3">Nobody really knows how these systems work</h3>
                <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                  Modern AI systems aren't built the way a bridge or a smartphone is. They're <em>grown</em> — trained on vast amounts of data through a process that adjusts billions of internal numbers until the outputs look right. Nobody designed those numbers; they emerged from training. And we have no reliable way to look inside and understand what the system has actually learned, or why it produces any given output.
                </p>
                <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                  This isn't just a theoretical concern. Researchers once found that a medical AI trained to assess pneumonia risk had learned to associate asthma with <em>lower</em> risk — not because asthma patients are healthier, but because they typically receive more aggressive care and so had better outcomes in the training data. The model had learned a pattern that was statistically real but medically backwards. Had it been deployed, it would have sent high-risk patients home.
                </p>
                <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                  If you can't understand what a system has learned, you can't reliably catch these failures before they cause harm — and catching them after the fact may be too late.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="info-card p-8">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-6">
              <div class="w-14 h-14 bg-gradient-to-br from-light-purple to-lavender rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
                <i class="fas fa-crosshairs text-2xl text-white" aria-hidden="true"></i>
              </div>
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3">Getting AI to reliably do what you actually want is harder than it sounds</h3>
                <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                  When you train an AI system, you can only reward it for behaviours you can measure. But what you can measure is never quite the same as what you actually care about — and capable systems find the gap. This is sometimes called <em>specification gaming</em>: the system achieves the metric you set while missing the point entirely.
                </p>
                <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                  A simple example: researchers trained an AI to win a boat racing game by collecting points. Rather than finishing the race, it learned to spin in circles crashing into point-scoring objects — technically optimal, completely useless. A higher-stakes version of the same problem: social media algorithms trained to maximise engagement learned that outrage and anxiety drive clicks, producing effects on mental health that were never anyone's objective but were a direct consequence of optimising for the wrong thing.
                </p>
                <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                  As AI systems become more capable and more autonomous — making decisions over longer timeframes without human review — the gap between "what we measured" and "what we wanted" can produce increasingly serious consequences.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="info-card p-8">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-6">
              <div class="w-14 h-14 bg-gradient-to-br from-durham-purple to-bright-purple rounded-xl flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">
                <i class="fas fa-balance-scale text-2xl text-white" aria-hidden="true"></i>
              </div>
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3">Governance hasn't kept up with capability</h3>
                <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                  Even if the engineering problems were solved, hard questions would remain: who decides how these systems get deployed? Who is legally liable when they cause harm? How do governments regulate technology that moves faster than legislation, built almost entirely by a handful of private companies with no legal obligation to publish safety evaluations before release?
                </p>
                <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                  There is also a coordination problem between major powers. The US, China, and EU are developing AI under different regulatory regimes and with different strategic incentives. If any country believes that slowing down for safety means falling behind, the pressure to cut corners is enormous — regardless of what individual researchers or companies want. This dynamic can produce bad outcomes even when nobody is acting in bad faith.
                </p>
                <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                  This is where political scientists, lawyers, economists, and policy thinkers are just as needed as computer scientists. The governance problem is not a technical one.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>

        <!-- Why "just keep it under control" doesn't cut it -->
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-bright-purple/15 to-light-purple/15 rounded-2xl p-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Why can't we just keep it under control?</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The most common pushback: if AI systems are tools we build and operate, surely we can design them carefully and switch them off if something goes wrong?
          </p>
          <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The honest answer is that this gets harder the more capable and autonomous a system is. A chess engine is easy to control because it only plays chess. A system that can browse the web, write and run code, send emails, and delegate subtasks to other AI systems is genuinely different — and that is roughly where frontier AI sits today, with capabilities still advancing.
          </p>
          <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            There are also strong commercial incentives pulling towards more autonomy, not less. The most economically valuable AI is AI that can handle complex tasks with minimal human supervision. Companies building the most capable systems are under pressure to deploy quickly. That pressure doesn't resolve on its own — which is exactly why governance matters.
          </p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 3: What's being done -->
  <section id="what-is-being-done" class="section section-neutral">
    <div class="site-container">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">

        <div class="text-center mb-12">
          <h2 class="section-heading text-3xl md:text-4xl mb-6">What's actually being done about it?</h2>
          <div class="section-divider"></div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed mb-8 text-slate-700">
          Quite a lot — though not yet enough. AI safety has grown from a niche concern into a serious field with significant funding, dedicated institutions, and real influence on how frontier AI labs operate.
        </p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 mb-10">

          <div class="program-card rounded-2xl p-6 text-center">
            <i class="fas fa-flask text-4xl text-durham-purple mb-4"></i>
            <h4 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Technical Research</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
              Interpretability (understanding what AI systems have actually learned), alignment, evaluations, and oversight — active research areas at academic labs and organisations like METR and Redwood Research, as well as within the major AI companies themselves.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="program-card rounded-2xl p-6 text-center">
            <i class="fas fa-university text-4xl text-durham-purple mb-4"></i>
            <h4 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Policy & Governance</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
              The UK's AI Safety Institute, the EU AI Office, and a growing body of academic work on liability, mandatory safety evaluations, and international coordination — trying to build frameworks that can actually keep pace with the technology.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="program-card rounded-2xl p-6 text-center">
            <i class="fas fa-users text-4xl text-durham-purple mb-4"></i>
            <h4 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Community & Education</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
              University groups like DAISI, training programmes, fellowships, and online courses — building a generation of people who understand both the technology and what's at stake.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div>

        <div class="info-card p-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Where you fit in</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            AI safety is genuinely short of people — not just ML engineers, but economists, philosophers, lawyers, political scientists, psychologists, and anyone who can think carefully about complex systems and hard tradeoffs. The field is young enough that people coming in now, from any background, can do work that actually shapes how things go.
          </p>
          <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
            You don't need to be a programmer to start. You need to be willing to engage seriously with difficult questions and take the stakes seriously.
          </p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

